1 If in the 90 's you 're adapting a book written in the 50 's , set the bloody thing in the 50 's and not the ' 90 's . See , 40 year old mores and values tend not to play as well , or ring as true , that far down the road . It 's a simple rule that Hollywood habitually keeps violating . And that 's the problem with this film . It should have been set in the era it was written in . You 'd think that would be a no - brainer , but nooo . I 'd elaborate , but bmacv 's comment spells it out quite well . I 'll limit my commentary to Rachel Ward . She looks like she dieted her ass completely out of existence for this role . As a result , she looks like a crack ho ' on chemotherapy , and is about as sexy as a gay leather couch in drag . I found her " I could die at any moment " look quite disconcerting , and it greatly detracted from her supposed " hotness " and the " sexual tension " the film intended to create . Other than that , the film was quite good ; a 7 + out of 10 .
